<section class="block-section do">
  <span class="section-tag">Do</span>
  <h2>Today's work — choose one path</h2>
  <p class="sub">All four paths end with a locked area and a current-state baseline. The path is about how you build that baseline.</p>
  <div class="choice-intro">
    <strong>Learning Intention:</strong> I have locked my Chennai area, described its current land use, and recorded a rough 15-minute-access baseline I can measure my redesign against.
  </div>
  <div class="choice-board">
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">A</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Read the cards and lock your area (default)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Work through the area data cards, pick your neighborhood, and write the current-state baseline: land-use mix, density, green-blue assets and losses, flood and heat exposure, who lives there, and a rough 15-minute-access percentage.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Default</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">B</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Propose your own area (stretch)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">If you want an area not on the cards (your own neighborhood, say), gather the same data yourself from maps and what you know, and build the card. Clear it with Mr. Ignash. The bar is the same: a real current-state baseline, not a vibe.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Stretch</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">C</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Source-test one data claim (choice)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Pick one number on your area card (a flood figure, a density, a green-cover share) and run it through the <a href="/ai-partners/the-source-evaluator/">Source Evaluator</a>. Whose number is it, what was it for, and what is its limitation? Planning data is rarely neutral, and knowing where a number came from matters. This is the start of the three sources your Plan needs OPVL'd: one municipal or government source, one community or NGO source, and one AI explanation.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Choice</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">D</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Peer-help — baselining 15-minute access (practice)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">If turning "can people walk to things" into a number feels impossible, come to the peer-help table. Estimate the access percentage for one shared area with a partner and Mr. Ignash, then use the method on your own.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Pairs · Practice</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="block-section show">
  <span class="section-tag">Show</span>
  <h2>What you're submitting today</h2>
  <p class="sub">Your locked area plus its current-state baseline. This is the starting line your redesign is measured from.</p>
  <div class="submission-callout">
    <div class="label">Area lock-in + current-state baseline</div>
    <p>Two things: (1) the Chennai area you are locking in, and (2) a one-paragraph current-state baseline covering its land-use mix, density, green-blue assets and losses, flood and heat exposure, who lives there, and a rough 15-minute-access percentage. Specific beats general: "about 45 percent of homes are within a 15-minute walk of a school, clinic, and market; the south end near the old eri floods every monsoon" clears the bar.</p>
    <a href="#" class="rubric-link">Submit via Google Classroom →</a>
  </div>
  <p class="rubric-meta">
    <strong>Rubric link:</strong> the current-state baseline is the K/U Area Profile on the <a href="/units/unit-6/assessment-sustainable-neighborhood-plan/">Sustainable Neighborhood Plan</a>. A specific, accurate baseline is what the K/U 7-8 band rewards, and it is what lets you prove your redesign moved something. See the <a href="/foundations/the-rubric/">rubric</a>.
  </p>
</section>

